Action.c(14):              <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(14):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(14):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(14):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(14):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(14):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(14):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(14):             <br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <strong>Correlation Challenge- Modrate</strong><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):         \r\n
Action.c(14):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(14):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(14):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(14):     \n

Action.c(14):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n

Action.c(14):         <div id="head_divStart" style="margin-left: 40px">\r\n
Action.c(14):              <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(14):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(14):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(14):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(14):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(14):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(14):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(14):             <br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <strong>Correlation Challenge- Modrate</strong><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):         \r\n
Action.c(14):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(14):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(14):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(14):     \n
Action.c(14):             manually navigate through the Challenge with no problems, but creating a \r\n
Action.c(14):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(14):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n
Action.c(14):             the end of this exercise by yourself, then you can correlate with the best of \r\n
Action.c(14):             them.<br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <strong>Notes</strong>:\r\n

Action.c(14):              <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(14):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(14):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(14):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(14):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(14):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(14):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(14):             <br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <strong>Correlation Challenge- Modrate</strong><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):         \r\n
Action.c(14):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(14):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(14):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(14):     \n
Action.c(14):             manually navigate through the Challenge with no problems, but creating a \r\n
Action.c(14):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(14):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n
Action.c(14):             the end of this exercise by yourself, then you can correlate with the best of \r\n
Action.c(14):             them.<br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <br />\r\n

Action.c(14):         <div id="head_divStart" style="margin-left: 40px">\r\n
Action.c(14):              <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(14):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(14):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(14):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(14):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(14):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(14):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(14):             <br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <strong>Correlation Challenge- Modrate</strong><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):         \r\n
Action.c(14):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(14):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(14):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(14):     \n
Action.c(14):             manually navigate through the Challenge with no problems, but creating a \r\n
Action.c(14):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(14):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n
Action.c(14):             the end of this exercise by yourself, then you can correlate with the best of \r\n
Action.c(14):             them.<br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <strong>Notes</strong>:\r\n
Action.c(14):             <br />\r\n

Action.c(101):              <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(101):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(101):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(101):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(101):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(101):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(101):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(101):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(101):             <br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(101):             <strong>Correlation Challenge- Modrate</strong><br />\r\n
Action.c(101):         \r\n
Action.c(101):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(101):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(101):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(101):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(101):     \n

Action.c(101):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(101):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n

Action.c(101):             them.<br />\r\n

Action.c(14):              <strong>What is Correlation in Load Runner?\r\n
Action.c(14):             </strong><br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             Correlation is used to obtain data which are unique for each run of the script and
Action.c(14):      which are generated by web server. Correlation provides the value to avoid errors arising
Action.c(14):      out of duplicate values and also optimizing the code. Automatic correlation is where we s
Action.c(14):     et some rules for correlation. It can be application server specific. Here values are repl
Action.c(14):     aced by data which are created by these rules. In manual correlation, the value we want to
Action.c(14):      correlate is scanned and create correlation is used to correlate.\r\n
Action.c(14):             <br /><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <strong>Correlation Challenge- Modrate</strong><br />\r\n
Action.c(14):         \r\n
Action.c(14):             <br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             Welcome to the Correlation Challenge. I have condensed some of the types of \r\n
Action.c(14):             correlation problems I have encountered in real web applications (ranging from \r\n
Action.c(14):             relatively easy, to fairly difficult) into this exercise. You should be able to \r
Action.c(14):     \n
Action.c(14):             manually navigate through the Challenge with no problems, but creating a \r\n
Action.c(14):             LoadRunner/VuGen script that will do the same thing will take a non-trivial \r\n
Action.c(14):             amount of effort. Please treat this as a training exercise. If you can get to \r\n
Action.c(14):             the end of this exercise by yourself, then you can correlate with the best of \r\n
Action.c(14):             them.<br />\r\n
Action.c(14):             <br />\r\n
